Functors in functional programming allow you to apply a transformation to the value inside an abstract data type without exposing its internal structure. In Rust, Option is perhaps the simplest example of such an idiom: it’s a functor because `Option<T>` can be mapped over with `.map()`, transforming the inner value safely only when it exists.

